<subSubSection id="C30FB2903524FFE8FF47FB75FE33FB15" pageId="7" pageNumber="363" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3524FFE8FF47FB75FE33FB15" blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1257]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B9613D093524FFE8FF47FB75FDB1FB5D" bold="true" box="[199,542,1159,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Distribution and Comments.</emphasis>
Known only from its 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93524FFE8FC9AFB7AFCE5FB5E" box="[794,842,1160,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Colombian Andes (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3524FFE8FB50FB75FA8AFB5E" box="[1232,1317,1159,1186]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-22@15.[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 57. Distribution of jumping spiders of the tribe Lapsiini Maddison (Salticidae: Spartaeinae) in South America. The figures with a dot inside represent the type species of each genus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501154/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93524FFE8FAECFB7AFA33FB5E" box="[1388,1436,1160,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="363">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected beating a rotten trunk and manually in the night over low vegetation in a high-Andean secondary moist forest.
</paragraph>
